    invoice-uploader-new                      5                                EXPLORER            INVOICE-UPLOADER-NEW     __pycache__       .claude       .venv       configs       __init__.py       settings.py       reports       src        invoice_uploader          automations            __init__.py           administration.py 2           launch_snelstart.py 2           login.py 2           read_invoices.py 2         tests         snelstart_automation.py 6       utils          __init__.py         config.py         logging_setup.py         ui_utils.py 1         wait_utils.py 4       .gitignore       CLAUDE.md       main.py 2       pyproject.toml       README.md       uv.lock        OUTLINE    TIMELINE               main.py 2       snelstart_automation.py 6         launch_snelstart.py 2        login.py 2       ui_utils.py 1       read_invoices.py 2       settings.py       wait_utils.py 4       administration.py 2                     src    invoice_uploader    automations     launch_snelstart.py    …         9  46  class LaunchAutomation:     def get_main_window(self, timeout: int = 30, interval: int = 5):                 Problems 21   Output  Debug Console  Terminal  Ports    wsl                                   Ctrl+K to generate a command                  Review smart wait system configurations                 can you look at my configs.settings, where i display the smart wait system and timout interval etc, how are thos used throughout my code?      Read settings.py and 5 other files and searched 4 times  Here's how your smart wait system and timeout interval settings from configs/settings.py are used throughout your code:   1. How the settings are exposed  In src/utils/config.py, the settings are wrapped in accessor functions: • get_timing_config(): Returns basic timing values (like WINDOW_TIMEOUT, WINDOW_CHECK_INTERVAL, etc.).  • get_smart_wait_config(): Returns a timing profile (fast/normal/slow) or defaults.  • get_wait_timeouts(): Returns a dictionary of timeout values, allowing environment variable overrides.     2. Where and how they are used  a. In Automation Classes  Each automation class imports and calls these config functions, typically in their constructor or setup: • src/invoice_uploader/automations/administration.py  • Imports: get_timing_config, get_wait_timeouts  • Usage: The class is set up to use these configs, but the current implementation only uses a hardcoded time.sleep(5) for waiting.   • src/invoice_uploader/automations/read_invoices.py  • Imports: get_timing_config, get_wait_timeouts  • Usage: Similar to above, but uses time.sleep(2) for button waits.   • src/invoice_uploader/automations/launch_snelstart.py  • Imports: get_timing_config, get_wait_timeouts  • Usage: Uses a hardcoded time.sleep(5) after launching the app, and has a get_main_window method that takes timeout and interval parameters (defaulting to 30 and 5, matching your config).   • src/invoice_uploader/automations/login.py  • Imports: get_timing_config, get_wait_timeouts  • Usage: Uses hardcoded time.sleep(2) for various login steps.     3. Summary of usage  • Config values are made available to all automation classes via the utility functions.  • Most actual waits in the code are still hardcoded (e.g., time.sleep(2)), but the structure is in place to use the config-driven values instead.  • The get_main_window method in launch_snelstart.py is the only place that directly uses the config values as parameters (for timeout and interval).     4. How to improve usage  To fully leverage your smart wait system: • Replace hardcoded time.sleep(...) calls with values from self.timing or self.wait_timeouts in each class.  • Use the config-driven intervals and timeouts for all waits, making the automation more robust and configurable.     If you want, I can show you how to refactor one of these classes to use the config-driven waits instead of hardcoded values. Let me know if you'd like to see that!     display where every timeout setting is used for in my code     Here is a breakdown of every timeout setting from your configs/settings.py and how (or if) each is used in your codebase:   1. WINDOW_TIMEOUT • Definition: WINDOW_TIMEOUT = 30  • Usage:  • Exposed via get_timing_config() in src/utils/config.py  • Used as a default parameter in get_main_window(timeout: int = 30, interval: int = 5) in launch_snelstart.py  • Purpose: Maximum time to wait for the SnelStart main window to appear.     2. WINDOW_CHECK_INTERVAL • Definition: WINDOW_CHECK_INTERVAL = 5  • Usage:  • Exposed via get_timing_config() in src/utils/config.py  • Used as a default parameter in get_main_window(timeout: int = 30, interval: int = 5) in launch_snelstart.py  • Purpose: Interval between checks for the SnelStart main window.     3. DEFAULT_ELEMENT_TIMEOUT • Definition: DEFAULT_ELEMENT_TIMEOUT = 30  • Usage:  • Used in get_smart_wait_config() and get_wait_timeouts() in src/utils/config.py  • Not directly used in automation classes, but available for use as self.wait_timeouts['element_timeout']  • Purpose: Intended as the default max wait for UI elements to appear.     4. DEFAULT_CLICKABLE_TIMEOUT • Definition: DEFAULT_CLICKABLE_TIMEOUT = 30  • Usage:  • Used in get_smart_wait_config() and get_wait_timeouts() in src/utils/config.py  • Not directly used in automation classes, but available for use as self.wait_timeouts['clickable_timeout']  • Purpose: Intended as the default max wait for elements to become clickable.     5. DEFAULT_WINDOW_READY_TIMEOUT • Definition: DEFAULT_WINDOW_READY_TIMEOUT = 30  • Usage:  • Used in get_smart_wait_config() and get_wait_timeouts() in src/utils/config.py  • Not directly used in automation classes, but available for use as self.wait_timeouts['window_ready_timeout']  • Purpose: Intended as the default max wait for a window to be ready.     6. DEFAULT_DIALOG_TIMEOUT • Definition: DEFAULT_DIALOG_TIMEOUT = 30  • Usage:  • Used in get_smart_wait_config() and get_wait_timeouts() in src/utils/config.py  • Not directly used in automation classes, but available for use as self.wait_timeouts['dialog_timeout']  • Purpose: Intended as the default max wait for dialogs to appear.     7. DEFAULT_TEXT_INPUT_TIMEOUT • Definition: DEFAULT_TEXT_INPUT_TIMEOUT = 30  • Usage:  • Used in get_wait_timeouts() in src/utils/config.py  • Not directly used in automation classes, but available for use as self.wait_timeouts['text_input_timeout']  • Purpose: Intended as the default max wait for text input fields.     8. DEFAULT_WAIT_INTERVAL • Definition: DEFAULT_WAIT_INTERVAL = 0.5  • Usage:  • Used in get_smart_wait_config() and get_wait_timeouts() in src/utils/config.py  • Not directly used in automation classes, but available for use as self.wait_timeouts['wait_interval']  • Purpose: Intended as the default interval between wait retries.     9. DEFAULT_CLICKABLE_INTERVAL • Definition: DEFAULT_CLICKABLE_INTERVAL = 0.2  • Usage:  • Defined in settings, but not used anywhere in the codebase.  • Purpose: Intended for interval between checks for clickability (not yet implemented).     10. DEFAULT_WINDOW_READY_INTERVAL • Definition: DEFAULT_WINDOW_READY_INTERVAL = 0.5  • Usage:  • Defined in settings, but not used anywhere in the codebase.  • Purpose: Intended for interval between checks for window readiness (not yet implemented).     11. TIMING_PROFILES • Definition: Dict of timing profiles (fast, normal, slow)  • Usage:  • Used in get_smart_wait_config() in src/utils/config.py to select a profile based on environment variable.  • Not directly used in automation classes, but values are made available via get_wait_timeouts().  • Purpose: To provide grouped timing settings for different system speeds.     Summary Table  Setting Used in Code? Where/How Used Purpose   WINDOW_TIMEOUT Yes get_main_window in launch_snelstart.py Max wait for main window  WINDOW_CHECK_INTERVAL Yes get_main_window in launch_snelstart.py Interval for window check  DEFAULT_ELEMENT_TIMEOUT Indirect Available via config, not directly used Max wait for UI elements  DEFAULT_CLICKABLE_TIMEOUT Indirect Available via config, not directly used Max wait for clickable elements  DEFAULT_WINDOW_READY_TIMEOUT Indirect Available via config, not directly used Max wait for window ready  DEFAULT_DIALOG_TIMEOUT Indirect Available via config, not directly used Max wait for dialogs  DEFAULT_TEXT_INPUT_TIMEOUT Indirect Available via config, not directly used Max wait for text input  DEFAULT_WAIT_INTERVAL Indirect Available via config, not directly used Wait retry interval  DEFAULT_CLICKABLE_INTERVAL No Not used Intended for clickable check interval  DEFAULT_WINDOW_READY_INTERVAL No Not used Intended for window ready check interval  TIMING_PROFILES Yes Used in config to select timing profile Grouped timing for system performance     In summary: Most timeout settings are made available to your automation classes via config accessors, but only WINDOW_TIMEOUT and WINDOW_CHECK_INTERVAL are directly used in logic. The rest are ready to be used for more robust, configurable waits, but are not yet actively applied in the automation steps (which currently use hardcoded time.sleep(...) values).
